Oct 4 2009 	Quaint little hotel in a fabulous location	This was my second trip to San Francisco and my main requirements from a hotel were that it was convenient to sights and/or transport, it was clean and it had character. The Cornell certainly fulfilled all these requirements although I am not sure I would stay there again.The location is about as good as they come - a few steps from Powell St where the cable cars run and only a few blocks from Union Square and the transport hub on Market St. It's nowhere near as noisy as hotels that are in Union Square and the Tenderloin district must be though - walking near those areas at night was enough to convince me they'd be a bit interesting. Bush St can be very busy, but I had a room on the side of the hotel away from its bustle.I booked a &quot;cosy queen&quot; room and was pleasantly surprised - for a single traveller it was quite spacious. It probably would be very cosy for two but still okay. The one part I would call cramped was the bathroom - I had to walk sideways to get between the basin and the toilet and to get into the shower. I'm not small, but I'm not huge either. I found it amusing to sidle around but some may find this annoying. I was on the sixth (top) floor with cute wallpaper, Modigliani prints and country style furniture. The bed was extremely comfortable to my surprise (I was half expecting lumpy.)Breakfast is nice if you like American style but don't dare ask for anything other than what they offer you, which is strictly french toast or eggs (&quot;done any style!&quot;) I was at the end of a month-long trip and just wanted some plain toast on my final day - even though toast came with the eggs, they refused to serve me just toast and insisted I had to have eggs or french toast. I also don't recommend this hotel if you like sleeping in (thankfully I don't sleep late). Breakfast is only from 7:30-9AM on weekdays and if you're not careful, housekeeping will enter your room before you're ready. A few days I had them knocking before 9AM and the final day when I returned from breakfast there was someone in my room to spray the shower with bleach before I had used it! I had no privacy sign so I was a little jumpy. Had I chosen to shower before breakfast, he probably would have entered the room when I was showering.The Cornell is a nice hotel with plenty of San Francisco character and it's quite good value. My stay was pleasant but unremarkable.	
Sep 14 2009 	Central Great Price Full Breakfast Included!	The Cornell Hotel is a charming, small hotel right in the Union Square area of San Francisco. It was recommended to me by my father who stayed there a few years ago and loved it. My husband and I requested a large Queen room and were given a room facing onto Bush Street on the 3rd floor. It was roomy with a desk and large dresser. The bathroom was just fine - clawfoot tub that had a really nice shower.The staff we dealt with were all quite friendly, both on checking in and out and on dining (complimentary breakfast in the Jeanne d'Arc Restaurant in the basement). The breakfast is your choice of french toast or eggs, toast, bacon and potatoes. Included is coffee, orange juice and a selection of cold cereals. We did leave a tip each morning for the server and felt that $135 for the room and breakfast was a fantastic deal even if tip wasn't included.The hotel is just perfect as it's about 2 blocks from Union Square so it's outside of the most congested area and a bit quieter but so close to everything. The gates to Chinatown are a few blocks down on Bush Street and the fabulous restaurants of Union Square are right around the corner (ie: Michael Mina, Grand Cafe). Nob Hill is a couple of blocks uphill. The cable car stops right at the corner of Bush and Powell which is steps from the hotel. We took the BART from the airport as the stop is about 4 blocks from the hotel. That last block is fairly steep so be prepared with good footwear - though I saw many women in heels doing just fine!I slept very well on both nights though my husband was kept awake by people yelling and talking on the street outside on our first night. The traffic quiets down overnight considerably - it was almost silent. We were very happy witht the comfort and the price of this hotel, but if you are someone who is used to the crisp sheets, matching furniture and room service of a more expensive hotel, this may not be the place for you. The funiture is old and worn as are the sheets. This didn't really bother me as it reminded me of sleeping at my grandmother's home when I was a kid. The mattress was comfortable and the pillows were just fine.We will definitely stay there when we go back to San Francisco.	
