Mar 12 2009 	Unique small conveniently located	My husband and I had been to San Francisco many times, but this was the frist time with our 4.5 and 9 year olds in tow while he spent the day in business meetings. We decided to forego the conference hotel in favor of one of a simpler and more personalized experience at a smaller hotel. We were not disappointed by the Cornell Hotel de France. In fact, I am surprised at some of the negative reviews. Having stayed at the near-by Golden Gate Hotel on previous visits, we knew that the Bush Street location cannot be beat with its walking proximtity to shops, cable cars, and Chinatown. I never had any concerns walking about either alone or with my children, and we walked a lot! Yes, there are steep hills -- but it's San Francisco! And the Nob Hill Review is what it is; sure, 'live nude men' are inside, but nothing untoward is outside the building. The conveniences offset any issues I could have dreamed up about these things. Plus, I loved having a coin-operated laundry within a block. We paid extra for parking through the hotel's arrangement with a public garage across the street with in/out privileges; this was a must for us. Urban parking prices can be steep, but this was within expected limits. The hotel itself was simply darling and showed a lifetime of personalized touches. As mentioned in other reviews the decor is of French reproductions, with differently 'themed' French artists for each floor that provided us with interesting conversations with our kids. The hotel was in good repair, the bathroom spacious, and our two adjoining rooms kept very clean. The rooms were indeed small and crowded, made even smaller by adding a roll-away for our littlest one. We were prepared for all of that and since we were not spending much time in our rooms anyway, this was not an issue. We thought the rates were very reasonable, and were delighted that the hotel could accomodate us with an extra night over the busy July 4 weekend. Best of all, breakfast was included in the charming restaurant in the basement; it was very good and service was excellent. The Chinese employees at the hotel were friendly and helpful and we found the front reception staff to be cordial, accomodating, and private. The kids loved seeing the staff dogs, too. Internet access is limited to a computer in the lobby, but it was reasonably priced and there was never a wait for the short check-ins we needed to make. Our rooms had windows looking toward the Powell St cable car line, which delighted our children. Even with that, our stay was as quiet as an urban hotel can be and definitely restful. I'd definitely go back and wouldn't hesitate to recommend this hotel to other families with children who are used to traveling. I think if you are traveling with very young children and are used to the sanitized glitzy amenities of over-priced big box hotels, this isn't going to please you...but that's my bias exposed, I guess. We've stayed in plenty of places like that over the year, but prefer the personalized touches of Cornell Hotel.	
