Sep 14 2004	A Marvelous Little Hotel	My sons and I had a great stay at the Cornell. Understand that the rooms are small, but as for location, one could hardly ask for more--the cable cars run right by it. The restaurant was excellent; the breakfast (included with our stay) far surpassed my expectations--this was no continental breakfast. From the old-fashioned elevator to the golden retriever in the hall, the place is utterly charming. Given the room rate was very reasonable, I could not have been more pleased.	
Sep 14 2004	Stopping at the Cornell; intimate excellent restaurant!	A delightful hotel; small, intimate and friendly. My wife and I have stayed there for the past 14 years on our trips to the City. The restaurant, which offers a free continental breakfast (eggs, toast, tea, coffee, juice) has a special surprise that took us a few years to discover: the dinners are exquisite! It's tempting to pass it up because of all the wonderful places to eat in the City, but it's well worth it to stay in and enjoy the hotel's restaurant. The staff is warm, friendly and attentive. The rooms have been remodeled (slightly) and the ones with views on Bush are the most coveted. The old elevator harkens back to those in Paris in 1920. Each floor is dedicated to a French painter. I would wholeheartedly recommend the Cornell, which is within walking distance of Union Square (down Powell), Chinatown (east on Bush) and right on the Powell cable car line. I have no complaints about the Cornell; we've also stayed at the St. Francis, Villa Florence (once the Manx), the Sir Francis Drake, Chancellor, Canterbury, King George and the Palace. Each is unique, just as is the small, intimate Cornell. It's the staff and restaurant and cozy rooms that bring us back.	
Mar 23 2004	A wonderful little hotel	This is a lovely hotel. Flowers welcome you as you enter the lobby and the entire facility is in pristine condition. In my opinion, the location is the best in town. The Cable Car stop is practically at your doorstep. Union Square, Market Street, and Chinatown are all within easy walking distance. There are restaurants and shops galore.My single room was tastefully decorated and could not have been cleaner. The bed was a dream to sleep on. In addition, the room was unbelievably quiet. Breakfast was included in the rate and it was delightful. Served in the dining room, each table was covered with linen and adorned with fresh flowers. A different juice was served each morning along with a robust coffee. A choice of hot cereal was followed by a delicious combination of eggs, hash browns, bacon, toast and slice of fruit. French Toast was also an option. The staff was absolutely great!By all means, dine at the hotel restaurant. I took advantage of the weekly rate and enjoyed five marvelous French meals. Each included a hearty soup and generous basket of delightful bread. Salads were fresh and creative, entrees were expertly prepared, and deserts were absolutely divine. I cant say enough about the superb service. My waiter, Dan, was perfectly attentive without being fussy.I adore the Cornell - a fantastic discovery. I cant wait to go back.	
Dec 15 2003	San Francisco charm	We spent just three days in November at the Cornell and found it charming with all the character of an older San Francisco boutique hotel that we expected. I have used at least 15 San Francisco hotels over the past few years ranging from the best to moderate hotels and this is the first time I will definately book our next visit at the same place. When staying dont forget to greet the owners wonderful dog &quot;Bon Jour Noel&quot; and he will respond accordingly.	
Nov 29 2003	Doesn't deliver not even close.	My &quot;medium size&quot; room was not worth the ninety dollars plus 15% tax plus sixteen dollars a day parking. It had very noisy steam heat that worked only part of the time and there wasn't even a toilet paper holder in the bathroom. There was just a roll of paper sitting across the b'room--not at all convenient. The prix fix dinner was just fair. Veggie overcook and potatoes stale. I left early so I wouldn't have to stay in that flop-house room.	
Nov 23 2003	French Style and Charm Great Location Incredible Value	I travel regularly to S.F. My wife and I stayed here for a weekend after reading about the hotel in Sunset magazine. I kow stay there regularly for business. If you want to feel like San Francisco is a place that real people visit and get some of the charm you experienced when you were last in Paris, consider this hotel. It is small and European. Each floor is dedicated to a different Impressionist artist, and features that artist's paintings on the hallway walls. The staff are friendly and speak French or Chinese. The rooms are small and clean. It's never been noisy although it is near the cable cars and bustling Union Square. Price includes breakfast in the charming restaurant in the basement.Cool tip: Arrive by BART and take the Powell St. cable car up to Bush. The hotel is 3 doors down to the left.	
Jul 29 2003	NY Times travel section does it again!	Not knowing anything about San Francisco, I did not realize that this gem of an intimate hotel is located literally seconds from the Powell St. Cable Car, walking distance to Chinatown, the theatre district, discount ticket center, shopping, restaurants galore, the wonderful Huntington Hotel with a piano bar and friendly bartender, the Muni, etc. My room was $75 per night, including a wonderful breakfast with excellent service in a true French cellar decorated with Jeanne D'Arc memorabilia. You could practice your french here too. Dinner was also superb. A definite find. Note, my room was for a single, but with a queen size bed. Very good quality bed too! website for the hotel: www.cornellhotel.com. Tell them Barbara from NY sent you!	
Dec 12 2002	Repeat Customer	My husband and I have stayed at the Cornell 5-6 times in the last three years. We love it. Great service, clean, rich in character, and the restuaurant Jeanne D'arc is superb. We've tried both the &quot;cozy&quot; rooms and the larger options. The &quot;cozy&quot; rooms are small, but -- as many have said before -- who goes to the City to hang out in a hotel room? Besides, sometimes you can get the &quot;cozy&quot; rooms for $65 per night, including that wonderful, yummy full breakfast. What a bargain!Kathleen EnnisJack Souza	
Sep 22 2002	Hotel Cornell Great Secret!	Couldn't find a review anywhere for this Hotel, but stayed there. It was wonderful! We had the smallest room, (which was very small), but it was extremely clean, the bed was comfortable; a desk; small TV; dresser. No tub, just a shower, but it was fine; quiet; the breakfast was a full cooked to order served breakfast with juice, coffee or tea, cereal and either french toast or eggs/bacon/toast and hashbrowns. Beautifully decorated. The larger rooms are also wonderful, for not much more money. Would recommend to anyone at anytime for a room with character - not your &quot;cookie cutter&quot; type of standard hotel rooms.	
